  <!-- H2 #6 — FRIDAY NIGHT PROBLEM -->
  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>The SoCal Friday night problem — bar refrigeration failure dynamics</h2>
      <p>
        The most expensive Beverage-Air call we run is the Saturday-morning one — the bar manager opens up to a dead
        HR back-bar cooler, six cases of beer at ambient temperature, a service window closing in eight hours, and
        no spare unit on the floor. That call costs the bar thousands in pre-weekend re-stocking, pulled service,
        and customer-facing inventory loss. The Friday-evening version of the same call — when the cooler is warming
        gradually during Friday service and the bar manager catches it at 45°F instead of 55°F — costs a fraction of
        that. Both are the same unit failing at the same point in its lifecycle. The only variable is when the call
        comes in.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is why our techs push LA bar operators into a preventive maintenance contract on Beverage-Air bar
        refrigeration specifically. Quarterly condenser cleaning, annual gasket replacement, semi-annual thermostat
        calibration, and refrigerant pressure check — the BA bar preventive visit runs $250-$380 per unit per visit
        and it keeps a 2023-vintage HR alive and reliable well past its 10-year design horizon. The math for the
        operator is straightforward, and our dispatch team runs the preventive route on Mondays, Tuesdays, and
        Wednesdays so the bar is clean going into the Friday service window.
      </p>
      <div class="fact-block">
        <h3>The failure modes that hit Friday</h3>
        <p>
          Door heater element failure on freezer-variant HRs (ice ridge forming at the jamb, doors binding on open).
          Gasket compression loss from thousands of shift-cycle opens. Condenser thermal overload on grease-packed
          fin spacing. Compressor start-relay failure on 8-plus-year units. All four are visible on a preventive
          maintenance visit before they become Friday-night emergencies. That's why we push the maintenance route
          instead of the emergency-response route.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

